First, what is a Collector?
ğŸ‘‰ A Collector is used at the end of a stream to collect the processed data
into a final form.
ğŸ“Œ collect() is the terminal operation
ğŸ“Œ Collectors is a utility class that provides ready-made collectors
1ï¸âƒ£ Collectors.toList()
ğŸ“Œ Converts stream into a List
2ï¸âƒ£ Collectors.toSet()
ğŸ“Œ Converts stream into a Set (removes duplicates)
3ï¸âƒ£ Collectors.toMap()
ğŸ“Œ Converts stream into a Map (key â†’ value)
Map<Integer, String> map =
    list.stream()
        .collect(Collectors.toMap(
            s -> s.getId(),     // key
            s -> s.getName()    // value
        ));
âš ï¸ Important: Keys must be unique, otherwise exception occurs.
ğŸ§  Interview Tip:
If duplicate keys â†’ provide merge function
4ï¸âƒ£ Collectors.counting()
ğŸ“Œ Counts elements in stream
5ï¸âƒ£ Collectors.summingInt()
ğŸ“Œ Sums values
int totalMarks =students.stream()
        .collect(Collectors.summingInt(Student::getMarks));
Related:
->summingLong()
->summingDouble()
7ï¸âƒ£ Collectors.maxBy() / minBy()
ğŸ“Œ Find max or min element
Optional<Student> topper =
    students.stream()
        .collect(Collectors.maxBy(
            Comparator.comparing(Student::getMarks)
        ));
ğŸ§  Returns Optional â†’ may be empty
8ï¸âƒ£ Collectors.groupingBy()
ğŸ“Œ Groups elements by a property
Map<String, List<Student>> groupByDept =
    students.stream()
        .collect(Collectors.groupingBy(Student::getDepartment));

ğŸ§  Real-life:
Students grouped by department
Employees grouped by role
Orders grouped by status
With counting:
Map<String, Long> countByDept =
    students.stream()
        .collect(Collectors.groupingBy(
            Student::getDepartment,
            Collectors.counting()
));
9ï¸âƒ£ Collectors.partitioningBy()
ğŸ“Œ Splits into two groups only (true / false)
Map<Boolean, List<Student>> result =
    students.stream()
        .collect(Collectors.partitioningBy(
            s -> s.getMarks() > 60
));
ğŸ”Ÿ Collectors.joining()
ğŸ“Œ Joins strings
String names =
    list.stream()
        .collect(Collectors.joining(", "));

Result:
Ram, Shyam, Mohan
With prefix & suffix:
Collectors.joining(", ", "[", "]");